  urldate = {2025-11-10},
  abstract = {Many physicians have adopted value-based care through accountable care programs via traditional Medicare (TM), which pay based on health risks and outcomes at the beneficiary level, and through Medicare Advantage (MA) plan partnerships. Relative to Medicare Fee-for-Service (FFS), these programs intend to better align clinician payments with incentives and flexibility to improve health and reduce health care costs. However, administrative burden and overpayment risks remain in these programs due to Medicare's risk adjustment mechanism.Risk adjusting Medicare payments has been essential in supporting plans and clinicians to provide innovative care for beneficiaries with predictably high costs. Beneficiary-level payments have always been adjusted based on the empirical association between diagnoses reported on FFS claims and total spending for beneficiaries in TM. With MA now covering more than half of all Medicare beneficiaries, and more than half of TM beneficiaries also now attributed to accountable care arrangements, risk adjustment is arguably Medicare's most important payment policy.},
